<br>
But more importantly they could do two big things.  <br>
<br>
This is how I see it:<br>
<br>
Your pet likes to stand NW(I think it's NW) of you.  If it can't do that (eg because you are too close to a wall there) then it wanders trying to find a way to get to it's favoured pixel relative to you.<br>
<br>
This could be fixed by having a &quot;Plan B&quot; or fallback postion, say, SE of you (all they would have to code is calculate if path takes it beyond a given range when following, and either warp it to the spot or, if the spot is in a wall, then warp it to alternate SE spot).<br>
<br>
<br>
In some spots if you /pet attack a target, your pet won't head straight to target, but will run/float about the dungeon looking for another way to the target than what you intended.  <br>
<br>
If the pathing in that spot can't isn't regarded as feasible to fix, then a calc as in first example could be made vs the mob, and if a pet would wander outside a given range of you to attack target then either it could warp back to you, or the attack could be cancelled with a &quot;that is not a legal target at this time, master&quot; type comment/effect, telling you it can't path directly to mob, and you have to get into a better position to sic pet on target.<br>
<br>
I think these two related codings would be relatively cost/time effective for VI, and would make pets in dungeons much, much safer...leading to much, much happier mages/necros/chanters/shamen/groupmates of pet casters/etc.<br>
